","display_name":"Charles Frederick Hale, M.D."},"birth":{"year":1827,"month":8,"day":15,"city":"Hartford","county":"Hartford County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"country":"United States"},"residence":{"city":"Forest Hill","county":"Kanawha County","state":"West Virginia","country":"United States"},"burial":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"I00626","father_name":"Frederick A. Hale","mother_id":"HD4160","mother_name":"Julia Stiles Hale"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00627","date_year":1853,"date_month":6,"date_day":26,"location_city":"New York City","location_county":"New York County","location_state":"New York","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1859,"children_ids":["HD4169","HD4170"]}],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST001","type":"preparatory","notes":"Hartford, CT. Preparatory education at Hopkins Grammar School in Hartford CT — same school later attended by Sherman Day Thacher (I00592, founder of The Thacher School)."},{"school_name":"Trinity College","dates":"1851","type":"graduate","notes":"Hartford, CT. A.M. degree 1851."},{"school_name":"University of Maryland, Medical Department","dates":"1849-1850","notes":"Baltimore, MD. Entered Oct 1849 — Mar 1850."},{"school_name":"College of Physicians and Surgeons","dates":"1850-1855","type":"medical","notes":"New York City. Entered Oct 1850. Graduated March 1855 with M.D."}],"career":[{"role":"Chief Medical Officer","organization":"Panama Railroad Company","start_year":1853,"notes":"Approximately 1853. The Panama Railroad — completed 1855 — was the first transcontinental railroad in the Americas and a major engineering project of the era, with high disease mortality among workers."},{"role":"Physician (private practice)","organization":"New York City","start_year":1855,"end_year":1859,"notes":"NYC private practice until c.1859, when he quit partly for impaired health and partly for business interests in West Virginia."},{"role":"President","organization":"Forest Hill Mining Co. (Coal Valley, West Virginia)","start_year":1859,"end_year":1862,"notes":"President of the Forest Hill Mining Co. at Coal Valley WV from 1859-1862. Operations suspended in 1862 due to the Civil War; Forest Hill is in modern Kanawha County WV."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST001","relationship":"alumnus"}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["physician"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Panama Railroad Chief Medical Officer about 1853","body":"Charles Frederick Hale graduated A.M. from Trinity College in Hartford 1851, took his M.D. from the College of Physicians and Surgeons NYC, and around 1853 served as Chief Medical Officer of the Panama Railroad Company — the first transcontinental railroad in the Americas, then under construction across the Isthmus. The position handled the engineering project's notorious tropical-disease mortality among workers."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Wife died at thirty, six years married","body":"Charles married Sarah Silvia Sibree (daughter of Robert Sibree of Bath, England) in New York City on June 26, 1853. She died at NYC on September 11, 1859 at age 30 years and 20 days, leaving two young children: Mary Astrea (4) and Charles Brinley (1). His subsequent move to Forest Hill WV in 1859 — President of Forest Hill Mining Co. — coincided with his widowhood."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"Henry Reed Stiles, The Stiles Family in America (1895), entry 419 with footnote"}]